For random variables X, Y with finite expectation, constants a, b ∈ ℝ, and σ-algebra F:

E[aX + bY | F] = a·E[X | F] + b·E[Y | F]   a.s.

This holds almost surely (conditional expectations are defined up to null sets). It extends to finite linear combinations, and to countable sums under suitable integrability conditions (e.g., monotone or dominated convergence). The property follows directly from the defining integral equation ∫_A E[Z|F] dP = ∫_A Z dP for all A ∈ F, combined with linearity of the Lebesgue integral.